{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"855446a0-9b1a-4808-97ea-06fda4d4f0dc","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root, for consistency)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `EnableMSTestRunner` | Switches from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner (built into MSTest 3.8.0) |\n| `OutputType` | Required — test projects become self-contained executables |\n| `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` | Lets `dotnet test` drive the new platform (otherwise only `dotnet run` works) |\n\n## 2. Each test `.csproj` — add TRX package\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.0\" />\n```\n\nThe old VSTest `--logger trx` flag won't work. This package provides TRX support for the new platform. (If you use central package management, add it in `Directory.Packages.props` instead.)\n\n## 3. CI command change\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is passed to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. TRX files are written to each project's `TestResults/` folder as before.\n\n**No other changes needed** — your `[TestClass]`/`[TestMethod]` code, test filters, and `dotnet test --filter` all work unchanged.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90bc34fa-583c-432c-aa1b-90bc49628be7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level**: Enable Microsoft.Testing.Platform in each test project (or better, in a Directory.Build.props for consistency)\n2. **CI command**: Update the `dotnet test` command\n\nFor MSTest 3.8.0, the migration is straightforward:\n\n1. Add `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to each project, or better yet, to a shared `Directory.Build.props`\n\n\n2. Enable `dotnet test` integration by adding `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` to your project configuration\n3. For TRX logging output, the command syntax changes slightly with the new platform\n\nMSTest 3.8.0 has built-in support for Microsoft.Testing.Platform, so the main requirement is setting the runner to enabled and converting the test project to an executable format.\n\nFor TRX reports, I need to verify whether the extension comes bundled or requires a separate NuGet package. The `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package might need to be added explicitly, and the logger command would shift from `--logger trx` to something like `-- --report-trx` depending on how the platform handles it. With `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` enabled, `dotnet test` continues to work, but the reporting configuration changes.\n\nSetting up a `Directory.Build.props` file...","outputTokens":1304,"requestId":"703B:328887:EA9ECDA:100A1807:69F2A766"},"id":"df52a6e6-8f19-49c9-88ec-50ec84f8b9b9","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:51:11.175Z","parentId":"46acc709-5d32-44bd-a273-1805594fd323"}
